# Phase 3: Authentication & GitHub App Integration

**Status:** Not Started
**Depends on:** Phase 1 (VPS provisioned with public IP for webhook URL), Phase 2 (Database with `github_installations` table for storing install records)
**Depended on by:** Phase 6 (Dashboard API routes require `withAuth`), Phase 4 (Build system uses installation tokens to clone repos), Phase 5 (Deployment engine uses commit status API), Phase 7 (Preview deployments need webhook routing + PR comments)

---

## Goal

Users can authenticate via GitHub OAuth. The GitHub App is registered and can receive webhooks. Installation tokens can be obtained for API calls. Webhook events are validated and routed to handlers.

After this phase:
- The platform owner can log in via GitHub OAuth and receive a JWT session cookie
- All dashboard API routes are protected behind session-based auth
- A GitHub App is registered with correct permissions and webhook configuration
- The webhook endpoint validates signatures and routes events to typed handlers
- The platform can obtain installation-scoped Octokit clients for GitHub API calls
- Commit status updates can be posted on any commit in an installed repository

---

## Architecture Context

```
Browser                    Dashboard (Next.js 15)            GitHub
  |                              |                              |
  |-- GET /api/auth/github ----->|                              |
  |<-- 302 redirect ------------|                              |
  |-- OAuth authorize ----------------------------------------->|
  |<-- redirect with ?code= ------------------------------------|
  |-- GET /api/auth/github/callback?code=xxx -->|               |
  |                              |-- POST github.com/login/oauth/access_token
  |                              |<-- { access_token } ---------|
  |                              |-- GET api.github.com/user ---|
  |                              |<-- { id, login } ------------|
  |                              |-- verify allowed_user_id     |
  |                              |-- create JWT session         |
  |<-- Set-Cookie: session ------|                              |
  |                              |                              |
  |-- GET /api/auth/me -------->|                              |
  |<-- { userId, githubLogin }--|                              |

GitHub (Webhook)           Dashboard                    Core (handlers)
  |                              |                              |
  |-- POST /api/webhooks/github ->|                             |
  |                              |-- verify HMAC-SHA256         |
  |                              |-- parse event type           |
  |                              |-- handleWebhook(ctx) ------->|
  |                              |                              |-- switch(event)
  |                              |                              |   push -> queue deploy
  |                              |                              |   pull_request -> queue preview
  |                              |                              |   installation -> track install
  |<-- 200 { received: true } --|<-----------------------------|
```

---

## Environment Variables Required

| Variable | Source | Description |
|----------|--------|-------------|
| `GITHUB_APP_ID` | GitHub App settings page | Numeric App ID |
| `GITHUB_APP_PRIVATE_KEY` | GitHub App settings (PEM download) | RSA private key for JWT signing |
| `GITHUB_APP_WEBHOOK_SECRET` | Set during App registration | HMAC secret for webhook validation |
| `GITHUB_CLIENT_ID` | GitHub App settings (OAuth section) | OAuth client ID |
| `GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET` | GitHub App settings (OAuth section) | OAuth client secret |
| `JWT_SECRET` | Generated, stored in AWS Secrets Manager | Secret for signing session JWTs |
| `ALLOWED_GITHUB_USER_ID` | Hardcoded or env var | Owner's GitHub numeric user ID |
| `NEXT_PUBLIC_DASHBOARD_URL` | Deployment config | Base URL for OAuth redirect_uri |

All secrets stored in AWS Secrets Manager (provisioned in Phase 1). Loaded into the dashboard container as environment variables at runtime.

